I stand behind the products I sell, not just as a retailer, but as a active member of our gun community so I know how much it means to be able to depend on a product when you need it most. I am also a consumer of the same products I make available to you.

  THE RED DOT YOU WILL RECEIVE WILL BE BRAND NEW & FACTORY SEALED... the one I used to conduct field tests is for demo purposes and will not be sold.

  I ran this optic on one of my personal rifles and have been absolutely impressed with it. First time out with it, I zeroed in at 50 yds. Off the bench with sandbags I drove about 120 tacks down range with an average grouping of 3"-3.5"(Nothing impressive, but great for me). Next was a run-n-gun drill simulating CQB no more than 25 yds target distance with use of hard cover and barricades. Official IDPA targets were used, 120 rounds, all on paper except for 8. We then dismounted the optic, remounted it on the same rail space and drove 120 more tacks off the bench with an average grouping of 3"-4" but that might have been because my heart rate was way up at that point. After reviewing all the results this red dot passed my test and maintained zero even after the run-n-gun and remounting it.

  In my honest opinion, I don't think you can find a better optic at this price point. I really like the crispness of the red dot. I have 3 Aimpoint red dot sights(1 comp4, and 2 PRO's) and this red dot is just as crisp as my comp4 and actually looks better than my PRO's. From my own experience this optic provides the operator with lightning fast target acquisition and best serves its purpose in CQ situations of 100 yds or less. 

It doesn't matter if your using a rifle or a shotgun, this RDS is made to withstand high recoil and maintain zero after repeated fire. Built to withstand the elements, made of high strength aluminum alloy, this waterproof micro red dot features a multi-coated objective lens eliminates glare providing a highly visible reticle even in the brightest conditions. Featuring a riser mount with QD locking cam for operators who want to co-witness with iron sights.. Intensity of the 3.5 moa dot has 11 level adjustment settings for proper contrast against full range of background light. Windage and elevation is adjustable with 1moa click value.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Lightly Used GSG AK47/22 Folding Stock Pending Sale
postcontent:
The .22lr “Kalashnikov” manufactured by GSG represents much more than a small caliber “knock-off” of a famous rifle. 
The GSG-AK47 is not only a well-made rifle, common of the German engineering we have come to appreciate, but it actually bears the name “Kalashnikov.”
GSG is currently the only company in the entire world licensed by Mr. Kalashnikov to manufacture real, functioning firearms, and they have not taken this opportunity lightly. 
The low cost of shooting .22lr ammo is attractive, but not really at the expense of an unfamiliar rifle with awkward controls and an uncertain reliability aspect. 
Fortunately for those who of us who like military rifles, all these issues were not a factor with the GSG-AK47. 
The look, feel and controls are almost identical to the most heavily proliferated rifle system in the world. 
From the first time it is handled and shouldered the comfortable stock length give the shooter the real feel of a familiar rifle.
The magazine works and looks great and the accuracy potential is surprisingly good. 
Whether it is for low-cost training on the real system, a departure from the usual noise to give your neighbors a break, to help a youngster learn to handle this style rifle without the recoil and intimidation of the muzzle blast or just plain for fun. 
I think the GSG-AK47 will make a nice addition to any military firearms collection.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1947 Marlin 39a, 22 lever gun,S,L,LR, good solid gun, nice shooter! 1947 Model!
location: st charles, fenton,washington, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
I will start by saying that these are my all time favorite guns, from boyhood to this very day, and I have walked hundreds of miles through the woods toting one with me..
I own multiples of it, but my safe is getting full and I still have others I love too, so...
This is a "D" code serial number gun so that breaks down as a 1947 gun.
I am offering it as cash sale or as a trade option gun..seeing what the market will trade.
These guns are known as the longest continually produced guns in the world, and for good reason..,they are great little shooters, and they just work..all the look and feel of the old days gone by when we all had a .22 and took it everywhere we went..
This gun has nice walnut wood, in above average condition and this is a First variation gun that was made from 1946-1950. These First variation guns are the most valuable of the 1st thru 3rd variation guns, with values listed between $500-$650 for guns between 90-95%..I honestly don't see  hardly any of these at the big shows anymore, it is unusual to see more than 1 of them in a 1000 table show these days. Some shows I don't see any. Some shows I see old originals for sale at $2500, and fancy redone ones being offered at $3500...If you want one of those, I will fix you up too.. The age of these guns means that most are gone, in collections, or that folks are still shooting them daily and won't let go of em'. Lot's of folks are simply keeping them for their future generations to get..
This gun is a great gun to add to a collection as a shooter, or as a gun to redo and make a safe queen out of. All parts are fully functional, and the bluing is mostly intact on the receiver and the tang, with thinning showing on the barrel. I don't want to say it's museum quality because it isn't, and I don't have it priced like one that is either, so all things are relative. It is the second oldest one I have , and if I don't find another gun guy to adopt it, I will probably take it apart and have it re-done and put it away for my grandson to inherit some day. It just isn't easy to find these original 1st variation guns anymore, and Im hoping someone would rather have it and shoot it than put it in a safe to sit. I am of the opinion that these were made for shooting, but the older I get, the more I understand the safe queen admiration thing too...,so, let's see what happens. 
I am wide open to things I like and will trade for ,so if you have thoughts in mind, just fire away...I am anxious to hear what the market has to offer either way..
You can reach me on my cell at REDACTED. Im up till midnight every night, so text me anytime, but please, no calls after 9pm, please. Thanks, Joe

title: For Sale:  1910 German Luger with holster
postcontent:
German Luger made in 1910 by DWM. It is not import marked. All parts are matching except the magazine, which is an unnumbered fxo mag from WWII. It comes with one magazine and an epf 41 holster, also from WWII. According to the gentleman I got this from, it came back from Europe with this holster and magazine, though he did not give me any details on who brought it back, other than the GI was his uncle. The holster has a name scratched in the back which appears to be "CROCKETT."

The gun is in very good condition. It appears to have seen police service between the wars, as it has the sear block safety added. Also, the unit marking on the grip strap has been ground off, though you can still see ghosts of it on the inner surface of the grip strap with the magazine and grips removed. Has arsenal installed bolt hold open.  It is possible this gun saw military service in WWI, police service during the wars, then was put back into military service during WWII. The bore has strong rifling with light to moderate pitting scattered in it, but it is still a very shootable bore.  I have shot the gun and it is accurate and was 100% reliable with Fiocchi ammo, which is pretty close to the original German military specs.

The holster is in good solid shape with tight stitching. The strap has some cracking and wear, but it is still pliable, fully intact, and usable. There is no tool in the pouch. The pull strap is fully intact. It is a nice holster.

$1350 FIRM for the package face to face in Hickory, NC.  Not particularly interested in trades unless they are weighted in my favor enough to be worth selling trade goods, as I will be selling any trade goods to raise the cash I need out of this.
